<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="349" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,437,930]" pageId="4" pageNumber="349">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,314,545,570]" pageId="4" pageNumber="349">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. The external appearance of the 
<taxonomicName authority="Matsumura, 1926" authorityName="Matsumura" authorityYear="1926" box="[691,1009,545,570]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Sugitania" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="349" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[691,798,545,568]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="349">Sugitania</emphasis>
Matsumura, 
<number box="[950,1009,545,570]" pageId="4" pageNumber="349" value="1926.0">1926</number>
</taxonomicName>
, species is uniform and characteristic (Sugi 
<number box="[223,282,582,606]" pageId="4" pageNumber="349" value="1990.0">1990</number>
; Owada 
<number box="[388,447,581,606]" pageId="4" pageNumber="349" value="1995.0">1995</number>
; Owada 
<emphasis box="[554,614,581,605]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="349">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[625,685,582,606]" pageId="4" pageNumber="349" value="2010.0">2010</number>
), the species are best distinguished by their genitalia. This high external similarity is the reason of the surprisingly late recognition of the distinct species of the genus occurring often sympatrically and syntopically. The best overview of the genus is found in the revisional paper of Owada 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="349">et al.</emphasis>
(
<number box="[199,260,690,714]" pageId="4" pageNumber="349" value="2010.0">2010</number>
), which illustrates all known taxa, displaying the prominent genital differences between the speciesgroups of the genus. 
<taxonomicName box="[391,577,725,749]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Sugitania" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="349" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lepida">
<emphasis box="[391,577,725,749]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="349">Sugitania lepida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has, in comparison with the other Korean 
<taxonomicName box="[1068,1176,726,749]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Sugitania" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="349" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1068,1176,726,749]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="349">Sugitania</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species, 
<taxonomicName authority="Sugi, 1990" authorityName="Sugi" authorityYear="1990" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Sugitania" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="349" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="clara">
<emphasis box="[1280,1369,725,749]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="349">S. clara</emphasis>
Sugi, 
<number box="[151,210,762,786]" pageId="4" pageNumber="349" value="1990.0">1990</number>
</taxonomicName>
, somewhat longer and broader wings with less pointed forewing tip and darker, less rosy-brown suffused brown ground colour. The genital differences are discussed and shown in the mentioned literature sources and are illustrated in the gen. figs 
<number box="[443,503,834,858]" pageId="4" pageNumber="349" value="8.5" valueMax="10.0" valueMin="7.0">7–10</number>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
